  "result": "The fix is complete. Here's a summary of what was changed and why:\n\n## Summary\n\n**File modified**: `AnkiDroid/src/main/java/com/ichi2/libanki/TemplateManager.kt`\n\n### Root Cause\n\nThe card HTML page is loaded at `http://127.0.0.1:<port>/` (the AnkiServer base URL), but `parseSourcesToFileScheme()` was converting `<object data=\"file.svg\">` to `<object data=\"file:///path/to/media/file.svg\">`. This creates a **cross-origin situation**: the page origin is `http://127.0.0.1` while the SVG loaded via `<object>` has origin `file:///`. The browser's same-origin policy then blocks JavaScript from accessing `contentDocument` on the `<object>` element, causing the `\"Cannot read properties of null (reading 'querySelectorAll')\"` error.\n\n### Changes Made\n\n1. **Removed `<object>` from `parseSourcesToFileScheme`**: The `replaceWithFileScheme(\"object\", \"data\")` call was removed. Now `<object>` tags keep their relative URLs (e.g., `data=\"_keyboard.svg\"`), which resolve against the HTTP base URL (`http://127.0.0.1:<port>/_keyboard.svg`). The `WebViewAssetLoader` already intercepts these HTTP requests and serves the files from the media directory. Since both the page and the SVG are now at the same `http://127.0.0.1:<port>` origin, JavaScript can access `contentDocument` without issues.\n\n2. **Fixed `||` short-circuit bug**: Changed `||` (short-circuiting OR) to `or` (non-short-circuiting OR) in the chain of `replaceWithFileScheme` calls. The old code used `||` which means if the first call (for `<img>`) returned `true`, subsequent calls for `<video>`, `<audio>`, and `<source>` would never execute, leaving those tags unprocessed. Using `or` ensures all tag types are always processed.",
